    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-01-17T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-01-17T18:00:00-05:00" n="2"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d2">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851<gloss target="#t_G1">G</gloss>.00/1–1049:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Embassy in France</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-01-17T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 17, 1949—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>145. Daridan<note n="1" xml:id="d2fn1">Jean Daridan, Counselor of the French
                        Embassy.</note> has expressed to <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> same
                    view contained penultimate para <gloss target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> 107 Jan
                        10<note n="2" xml:id="d2fn2">Not printed.</note> qualifying his remarks
                    however with statement that he uninformed developments past ten days which might
                    explain optimism Overseas France officials in <gloss target="#t_urtel1"
                        >urtel</gloss> 106 Jan 10<note n="2" xml:id="d2fn3">Not printed.</note> re
                    negotiations with Bao Dai.</p>
                <pb facs="0019" n="5" xml:id="pg_5"/>
                <p>While <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> desirous French coming to terms with
                    Bao Dai or any truly nationalist group which has reasonable chance winning over
                    preponderance of Vietnamese, we cannot at this time irretrievably commit US to
                    support of native govt which by failing develop appeal among Vietnamese might
                    become virtually puppet govt, separated from people and existing only by
                    presence French military forces. Accordingly, Emb should make no additional
                    representations to French until and unless further instructed by <gloss
                        target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> which does not believe it desirable go beyond
                    position outlined <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 2637 Jul 14<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d2fn4">
                        <ref target="frus1948v06#pg_33">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1948, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">vi</hi>, p. 33</ref>.</note> its <gloss
                        target="#t_reftel1">reftel</gloss> 3621 Jul 9 from Paris<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d2fn5">
                        <ref target="frus1948v06#pg_31">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid</hi>, p. 31</ref>.</note> and <gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 5129 Sep 30.<note n="5" xml:id="d2fn6"
                        >Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> will inform Emb re possibility any common
                    anti-Communist action Indochina (third para <gloss target="#t_Embtel1"
                        >Embtel</gloss> 107) after it has recd Brit views as Emb London reports Brit
                        <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> has instructed Brit Emb Wash
                    discuss matter with <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
